🕰️ 1. Origin (1995)

Created by Brendan Eich at Netscape to make web pages interactive.
Initially named Mocha, later LiveScript, and finally JavaScript.
First appeared in Netscape Navigator 2.0.

📜 2. Standardization (1997–1999)

Standardized by ECMA International as ECMAScript (ES).
ES1 (1997): First version of the standard.
ES3 (1999): Added features like try/catch, better strings, and loops.
ES4: Planned but never released due to disagreements.

💻 3. Growth and Popularity (2000–2008)

Used mainly for form validation and simple browser effects at first.
AJAX (2005) revolutionized web apps by allowing data updates without reloading the page.
Enabled rich web applications like Gmail and Google Maps.
Libraries such as jQuery, Dojo, and Prototype made coding easier and more consistent.

⚙️ 4. Modern JavaScript (2009–2015)

Node.js (2009): Allowed JavaScript to run on servers, expanding its power.
ES5 (2009): Improved syntax and added JSON support.
ES6 (2015): Major update introducing let, const, arrow functions, classes, promises, and modules.

🚀 5. Framework Revolution (2015–Present)

Modern frameworks like React, Angular, and Vue.js made large-scale web apps easier to build.
JavaScript became essential for single-page applications (SPAs).
Regular ECMAScript updates (ES7, ES8, etc.) keep improving features.

🌐 6. Today’s JavaScript

Runs on both client-side and server-side (via Node.js).
Used in web, mobile, game, and AI development.
Continues to evolve, remaining one of the most powerful and versatile programming languages in the world.